    "content": "1: 10 -- Non-negotiable. The source text is Chinese; the output is English philosophical prose.\n2: 9 -- The essays are philosophy, not literature. A translator without philosophical training will flatten the arguments.\n3: 7 -- Important for 诗意 and 西西弗斯 essays, less so for the technical essays.\n4: 7 -- The formalism is load-bearing in two essays (范畴论与境, K1策略). Errors would be serious but the translator can consult experts.\n5: 8 -- The collection shifts register constantly: from the colloquial cat example to formal category theory to poetic 梦境 language, sometimes within a single essay.\n6: 7 -- Important for 后形而上学 and the 道德仁义礼 passages. But the author's usage deliberately departs from traditional readings, so over-reliance on established conventions could mislead.\n7: 9 -- This is what distinguishes translating these essays from translating standard philosophical texts. If the experiential sequences are disrupted, the essays lose their distinctive methodological contribution.\n8: 7 -- The author engages with existentialist and phenomenological concepts (荒谬, 现象, 感受, 清醒/沉醉) that need to land correctly for Western readers.\n9: 4 -- The Buddhist dimension exists but is not technically demanding in most of the essays. The author's 境 draws on Buddhist resonance but is defined independently. The translator can consult the Buddhism expert for specific terms.\n10: 8 -- The author explicitly invokes the Kantian parallel. English-language philosophical readers will use Kant as their primary reference frame. Getting Kantian terms right is important for the reception of the work.\n11: 4 -- The analytic philosophy of language engagement is concentrated in K1策略 and is already intertwined with the category theory formalism. Anscombe/Brandom-style register is not the primary mode of these essays.\n"
